<h2>Considerations</h2>

<p>
  We use a simple <code>&lt;div class=&quot;alert&quot;&gt;</code> structure
  with modifier classes (e.g., <code>alert--success</code>,
  <code>alert--danger</code>) so visual styling is predictable and easy to
  extend. Each alert includes an appropriate ARIA live-region role:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <code>role=&quot;status&quot;</code> for informational or success messages
    that should be announced politely,
    <a
      href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Accessibility/ARIA/Reference/Roles/status_role"
      >which is implicit when set</a
    >.
  </li>
  <li>
    <code>role=&quot;alert&quot;</code> for urgent or error messages that
    require immediate attention and announced assertively,
    <a
      href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Accessibility/ARIA/Reference/Roles/alert_role"
      >which is implicit when set</a
    >.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  Using semantic roles instead of JavaScript-driven announcements ensures
  reliability across assistive technologies, keeps the component lightweight,
  and aligns with accessibility best practices.
</p>

